The St. Tammany Parish Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness is receiving continual updates from the National Weather Service and is monitoring the tracks of this system. St. Tammany Parish has implemented its storm protocols and has placed Emergency Operations Liaisons on stand-by for possible activation.

post_text:
#ICYMI The installation of a FloodBreak Automatic Floodgate Mitigation System — in the Fox Hollow subdivision in the Slidell area is complete. This gate is the first of its kind in the State of Louisiana installed in a residential neighborhood. With the installation of this gate, the gap in the levee system will now be closed during a flood event. This system requires no man power to operate, and is automatically activated by flood waters which cause the gate to rise and protect the area where the gate is installed. As the flood waters recede, the gate recedes as well. No man power is required to operate the system. When not activated, the gate lies underground, flush with the roadway, and residents simply drive over it. It is touted as a “passive, automatic flood barrier system that provides permanent and virtually invisible flood protection without human intervention or power.”
#floodmitigation

Watch the video of the demonstration at this link:
http://75.131.66.146/CablecastPublicSite/show/1669?channel=1

Thank you for your patience!
The Bayou Lacombe drawbridge on the Tammany Trace remains in the down position and closed to marine traffic due to the mechanical failure noted one week ago. Crews have identified the issue, and the parts needed for repair are on order. Parish Government anticipates the arrival of the necessary parts within the next 24 hours. When the part arrives, the bridge will be repaired as soon as possible. We will continue to post changes and updates on the Tammany Trace website at www.tammanytrace.org, and on the Tammany Trace Facebook page.

St. Tammany Parish Public School System is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
Yesterday at 3:00 PM ·

We are awaiting details and further guidance to determine how we will safely transition to the next phase of our school attendance plan. This will take time and will not happen immediately. We will continue with the plan we currently have in place where beginning Monday, September 14, students in grades Pre-K to 5 return to school in-person five days a week, and students in grades 6-12 follow the hybrid model.

We will continue to follow health and safety protocols that are in place. We will provide an update and more information Friday, September 18. Please visit the district website at www.stpsb.org for the most up-to-date information.

Thanks for your patience and support as we work together for a safe and successful beginning to this school year.

#WeAreSTPPS

We are still in hurricane season. Please remember these generator operation safety tips:

❌DON’T place a generator inside of ANY structure
❌DON’T place a generator near open doors and/windows
❌DON’T refuel a generator when hot
shared_text:
Louisiana Office of State Fire Marshal
September 2 at 3:33 PM ·

Chief Browning traveled to Calcasieu Parish today to participate in a press conference with Entergy and Entergy Louisiana where he reiterated the warnings about generator safety:

❌DON’T place a generator inside of ANY structure
❌DON’T place a generator near open doors and/windows
❌DON’T refuel a generator when hot

We’ve got 2,500 signs sharing the same message going up in more than a dozen parishes with more than 1,000 power outages remaining.

He also visited with city and parish leaders about how the SFM can help them start rebuilding.

The work following #hurricanelaura is far from over...

Governor John Bel Edwards
Louisiana Governor's Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness

St. Tammany Parish Fire Protection District #2
August 29 at 9:26 PM ·

Our fellow 1st Responders in Southwest Louisiana are working tirelessly around the clock to continue to serve their communities. Many have lost everything, and are in desperate need of basic necessities. Fire District 2 will be planning on sending a shipment of these supplies this week.

Donations of water, non-perishable food items, personal hygiene, diapers, new in package personal clothing items i.e socks, underwear, t-shirts would be greatly appreciated.

Donations can be dropped off at Station 21 located at 424 Hwy 22 West Madisonville, LA. 70447. We are planning on making the trip to deliver on Wednesday. Please feel free to share this post to assist us in getting the word out.

St. Tammany Parish Fire Protection District #2
August 29 at 9:26 PM ·

Our fellow 1st Responders in Southwest Louisiana are working tirelessly around the clock to continue to serve their communities. Many have lost everything, and are in desperate need of basic necessities. Fire District 2 will be planning on sending a shipment of these supplies this week.

Donations of water, non-perishable food items, personal hygiene, diapers, new in package personal clothing items i.e socks, underwear, t-shirts would be greatly appreciated.

Donations can be dropped off at Station 21 located at 424 Hwy 22 West Madisonville, LA. 70447. We are planning on making the trip to deliver on Wednesday. Please feel free to share this post to assist us in getting the word out.

post_text:
We are saddened to hear of the passing of St. Tammany icon and world-renowned artist Ronnie Kole. Our condolences are with his family and friends. Thank you for all you gave to St. Tammany. St. Tammany Parish President Mike Cooper shared these words:

“Ronnie Kole was a well-loved artist, both locally and world-wide. He was a generous philanthropist, who devoted his life to his family, his music and his community. St. Tammany — and Louisiana — are better for having known him. He and his beloved late wife Gardner were the founders of Jazz on the Bayou, an event which for nearly thirty years, has been a major fundraiser for Easter Seals Louisiana, an organization they were such an integral part of for many decades, as well as many local non-profits including the Tammany Trace Foundation. He generously donated his time and talent to the St. Tammany President’s Arts Awards, and countless events to benefit Camp Salmen Nature Park. Ronnie Kole’s legacy will be lasting and unforgettable, and we will certainly miss him here in our community. My condolences are with his family and friends.”

The St. Tammany Parish Sheriff's Office will be on-hand to assist in the aftermath of hurricane #Laura
We wish them safe travels and safe return.
#InThisTogether
shared_text:
St. Tammany Parish Sheriff's Office
August 26 at 3:13 PM ·

Fifteen deputies with the St. Tammany Parish Sheriff's Office Special Operations Division are leaving at daybreak Thursday morning, headed to the Lake Charles area. The deputies are bringing with them six flat boats, eight 4x4 pickup trucks, chainsaws, generators, air compressors, life jackets, high water boots and many other supplies. They will be assisting law enforcement in Southwest Louisiana with search and rescue operations following Hurricane Laura.
Sheriff Randy Smith said officers from around the state and around the nation have come to our aide during storms in the past, and we are returning the favor.
“Our brothers and sisters to our west are about to experience a devastating storm and aftermath,” Sheriff Smith said. “We in St. Tammany know all too well what that is like. Going there to help is simply the right thing to do.”

shared_text:
US National Weather Service New Orleans Louisiana
August 25 at 6:16 PM ·

🌀 Latest 4PM CDT update on Hurricane Laura. Forecast track continues to show major impacts likely along the SW LA and E TX coastlines late Wed and Thu, with impacts stretching east to our area very possible.

Also, there are many watches and warnings in effect currently due to potential impacts from Hurricane Laura across southeastern Louisiana and southern Mississippi. Main focus will be on gusty winds generally W of the MS river, storm surge along coastal areas, heavy rain west of I-55 and isolated tornadoes.

Stay tuned for more updates.

shared_text:
Washington St. Tammany Electric
August 23 at 5:54 PM ·

Looks like we could get a 1————2 punch from Marco and then Laura. We are keeping a close eye on both of these storms. We have already started emergency preparations. We urge each of you to prepare now for these storms and expect power outages. Please take special precautions for those who rely on life support

Experience has shown there is no reliable means of determining if or when a hurricane may cause an electrical outage or how long such an outage may last.

Remember high winds from Hurricane Marco and Laura can cause electric lines to be torn down. These dangling lines and lines on the ground can be deadly

Call 1-866-672-9773 to report down lines, outages or any hazardous situation. Your cooperative is here for you 24 hours a day. Please stay safe and remember you can download our smart hub app.

August 22 at 7:45 PM ·

Current overview of all the watches now in effect across the area. Be aware of changing conditions as we go into later this weekend and early next week due to impacts related to Tropical Storm Marco. Hurricane/Tropical storm warnings could be required across parts of the area as Marco continues north towards the northern Gulf coast.

The watch phase is the vital time to have a plan in place. Review more information visit: https://www.weather.gov/wrn/hurricane-preparedness

More updates to come.

St. Tammany Parish Sheriff's Office
August 18 at 1:35 PM ·

Members of the STPSO Operations Division joined parish employees today to clean up a sandy area on the Bogue Falaya River located under the Boston Street bridge and Claiborne Hill Overpass. Many residents have been frequenting the area this summer to cool off in the river and unfortunately many have been leaving behind their trash and other debris. Sheriff Randy Smith urges all residents to pick up their litter and clean up after themselves. We in St. Tammany are blessed to have so many wonderful and beautiful waterways to enjoy; please don't ruin them by littering.

post_text:
Pool time can be fun and great exercise for children but also poses a dangerous risk. Drowning is the leading cause of unintentional death in children ages 1-4. Keep your family safer by practicing these simple #watersafety steps this summer:

1. Never leave a child unattended in or near water.
2. Teach children how to swim.
3. Teach children to stay away from drains.
4. Ensure all pools and spas - both in your backyard and any public pool you may visit - have compliant drain covers.
5. Install proper barriers, covers and alarms on and around your pool and spa.
6. Know how to perform CPR on children and adults.
7. Take the Pledge@ http://bit.ly/PledgePS

**FAUBOURG COQUILLE WATER SYSTEM**

Tammany Utilities will be flushing the Faubourg Coquille Water System on August 17th and August 18th. The flushing is anticipated to follow the schedule below, but is subject to change due to weather or other unforeseen circumstances. Tammany Utilities customers living in these areas can expect to experience low water pressure when flushing is initiated. Hwy 1085, Willowbend, Del Sol, Tuscany West, Diversified, Beau Arbre, Savannah Trace, Hidden Creek

*Tuesday, August 18th 9:00 p.m. – until*
Timber Branch, Innwoods, Hwy. 21, Maison Du Lac, Weston Glen, Tallow Creek

post_text:
Pool safety is always a concern when small children are around.

Remember to follow these safety tips:
1.Never leave a child unattended in or near water.
2. Teach children how to swim.
3. Teach children to stay away from drains.
4. Ensure all pools and spas - both in your backyard and any public pool you may visit - have compliant drain covers.
5. Install proper barriers, covers and alarms on and around your pool and spa.
6. Know how to perform CPR on children and adults.
7. Take the Pledge@ http://bit.ly/PledgePS

Even though summer time is coming closer to an end, the danger around pools doesn’t. A pool is just as dangerous in December as it is in July.

post_text:
Be Counted St. Tammany!

We are currently 2nd in the state with self-responses. If you have already filled out your census response - THANK YOU! If you haven't responded, you can do so easily online - and quickly. Go to www.2020census.gov to send your response today.

Why is the census important? From census.gov:

"When you respond to the census, you help your community gets its fair share of the more than $675 billion per year in federal funds spent on schools, hospitals, roads, public works and other vital programs. Businesses use census data to decide where to build factories, offices and stores, and this creates jobs."

post_text: From our friends at St. Tammany Parish Public School System
shared_text:
St. Tammany Parish Public School System is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
July 28 at 12:08 PM ·

STPPS will now begin the 2020-21 school year after Labor Day with “Safe Start Days” set for Sept. 8-11, following a School Board recommendation to delay school reopening. The first full day of school with all students is Monday, Sept. 14.

View all adjustments to the 2020-2021 calendar: www.stpsb.org/calendar.php.

The STPPS Virtual School and traditional STPPS brick-and-mortar schools will follow this calendar.

The determination if we start school with in-person, hybrid, or distance learning will be determined by the phase the state is in when school starts in September. More details on our plan by phase are available at http://stpsb.org/coronavirus/2020-2021/planning.html

We know it can be confusing as plans change and parents are asked to make important decisions for their children in an uncertain time. We will be here to walk you through it one step at a time. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we navigate this pandemic and changing situation together.

shared_text:
St. Tammany Parish Government
June 30 at 5:30 PM ·

Road construction on Brewster Rd. will begin on July 1st and will be a 45-calendar day project.

This project is a continuation of Brewster Rd. and will be from Summer Haven Ct. to Hwy. 1077. This is a reconstruct and will consist of milling the existing asphalt, mixing soil cement into the base material, and then finally repaving the asphalt. There will be signage and detail officers on site at both ends of the project when cutting the soil cement to let the travelers know there will either be long delays, or to go very slow to avoid getting the cement on the vehicles, and they can detour on Dummyline Rd.

In addition, Iris Dr. in Flowers estates will be reconstructed as well. This is from Zinnia Dr. to N. Azalea Dr.

Larry & Sandy Barrios Saluted by Keep St. Tammany Beautiful
CONGRATULATIONS!

Keep St. Tammany Beautiful (KSTB) recognizes Larry and Sandy Barrios for the litter-free and beautifully landscaped property at their home on North Military Rd. (Hwy. 1090) in the Slidell area. This honor is a project of KSTB to highlight outstanding property in the Military Road area. The Barrios own Larry's Dry Cleaning by Louis in Slidell and Picayune, Ms., a family owned and operated business since 1929. The Barrios are active members of the community and still find the time to keep their property maintained and admired by all who drive pass it on Military Rd.

PICTURE:
(Left to Right): Rick Moore, KSTB Director; Carroll Knowles, KSTB Board Member; Sandy Barrios; Larry Barrios; Sharon Snowdy, KSTB Board Member; Floyd Trasher, Constable; Mike Smith, District 9 Councilman. Not pictured Cathy Henderson, KSTB Board member.

text: The Boil Advisory for Countryside and Goodbee Square Subdivisions is lifted.

post_text:
Countryside and Goodbee Square Subdivisions
Today, a 10-inch water main along West Countryside Parkway near the entrance to Countryside Subdivision ruptured. Tammany Utilities had to turn the water off to make the repair. Out of an abundance of caution and in accordance with Louisiana Department of Health regulations, a boil advisory is in effect for all Tammany Utilities customers in Countryside and Goodbee Square Subdivisions. Customers wishing to consume the water should boil it for at least one minute. Tammany Utilities will rescind the advisory once sampling has confirmed that your water is safe to drink. Customers will be notified that the water is safe to drink by an automated phone call, signs placed throughout the neighborhood and notices on the Parish Government’s website and social media sites.

post_text: From the National Weather Service.
shared_text:
US National Weather Service New Orleans Louisiana
July 3 at 6:57 AM ·

A front will become stationary across the area for the holiday weekend. Occasional showers and thunderstorms are expected to develop each day, especially during the afternoon hours. A few storms could be strong with gusty winds, but the main threat will be the potential for very heavy rainfall in locations that receive multiple thunderstorms. While much of the area can expect 1-3 inches of rain by Monday morning, a few spots could see much higher totals. Anyone planning outdoor activities this weekend should keep a close eye on the weather, as these storms will be capable of producing a lot of lightning, along with the heavy rain potential.

post_text:
Road construction on Brewster Rd. will begin on July 1st and will be a 45-calendar day project.

This project is a continuation of Brewster Rd. and will be from Summer Haven Ct. to Hwy. 1077. This is a reconstruct and will consist of milling the existing asphalt, mixing soil cement into the base material, and then finally repaving the asphalt. There will be signage and detail officers on site at both ends of the project when cutting the soil cement to let the travelers know there will either be long delays, or to go very slow to avoid getting the cement on the vehicles, and they can detour on Dummyline Rd.

In addition, Iris Dr. in Flowers estates will be reconstructed as well. This is from Zinnia Dr. to N. Azalea Dr.

post_text:
The Louisiana National Guard’s State Aviation Command is set to conduct a flyover of Slidell, Hammond, Lafayette, Lake Charles, Alexandria, Shreveport and Monroe area hospitals to honor first responders and healthcare professionals who have been working the front lines of the COVID-19 response, July 1st.

The aviators are scheduled to send four UH-60 Black Hawk helicopters to fly over the hospitals in each region. They are scheduled to be in the Slidell and Alexandria areas at approximately 11 a.m., the Hammond area at approximately 11:10 a.m., the Lafayette and Monroe areas at approximately noon, the Lake Charles area at approximately 1:30 p.m. and the Shreveport area at 2:30 p.m.

#COVID19
#InThisTogether

From DOTD: Road or Lane Status for LA 40 @ TCHEFUNCTE RIVER BRIDGE

Beginning Monday, June 29, 2020, through Sunday, July 12, 2020, there will be a 24/7 single lane closure that will affect both Eastbound and Westbound traffic of LA 40. This is a long-term, temporary traffic configuration and traffic will be maintained by a temporary traffic signal. This closure is for crews to remove part of existing bridge and construct a portion of new bridge.

One lane will remain open in one direction at all times. Wide loads are still not permitted through this area at this time. There will be no other vehicle restrictions, and emergency vehicles will have access. Motorists may encounter a slight delay during this time.

post_text: Early voting for the July 11, 2020 Presidential Preference Primary and Municipal Primary Election will begin on Saturday, June 20, 2020 and ends on Saturday, July 4, 2020. Early voting hours are 8:30 A.M. to 6:00 P.M. daily thru the early voting period, and closed on Sunday. The Covington office is located at 601 N. Jefferson Ave., and the Slidell Office at 520 Old Spanish Trail in the Conference Area on the ground floor. The Mandeville Office is located at 21490 Koop Dr., Building A. Identification is required to vote. If additional information is needed, please call (985) 809-5500 or (985) 646-4125.

Following the launch of our new economic research publication The AnalyST in May, St. Tammany Corporation continues to provide timely, relevant, easy-to-understand data through our latest update “Snapshot: Impacts of COVID-19 on St. Tammany.”

This report shows us how the pandemic has changed the economic landscape in #StTammany as of June 2020 and provides context essential to our economic recovery moving forward: where are we now, where were we before, and where are we going.

post_text: Update on our hard-working St. Tammany Parish Public School System. #Classof2020 #COVID19 #InThisTogether
shared_text:
St. Tammany Parish Public School System
June 11 at 5:59 PM ·

After receiving feedback from our graduates, their families and the community, and working with the administrators of our high schools, we have decided to expand our modified graduation ceremonies to a more traditional format at each of the eight high school stadiums.

The graduation ceremonies will be held on the same dates. Final decisions on times will be made by Monday afternoon.

School administrators are expanding their previous plans to best meet the needs of their individual school community and will provide additional details as soon as they are available on each high school’s website.

For details and information: stpsb.org/Class-of-2020/

#STPPSGrads

WSTE.COOP
Washington / St. Tammany Electric Coop

Washington St. Tammany Electric
June 7 at 4:30 PM ·

Washington St Tammany Electric will continue to monitor the storm as it spreads across Washington, St Tammany and Tangipahoa parishes. We are beginning to see the affects of the wind from Tropical Storm Cristobal. The mix of a saturated ground and wind causes tree limbs, trees and power poles to fall. Please stay away from any dangling line or lines on the ground. Call us to report any hazardous conditions or outages at 1-866-672-9773 or use your WSTE smart hub app. Visit our website at www.wste.coop and follow power outages by clicking “Storm Center” then “view outage map”.
Please use our outage number orSmart Hub to report your outage. Currently we have very few outages

post_text:
Great News!
#ClassOf2020
shared_text:
St. Tammany Parish Public School System
June 4 at 10:20 AM ·

Modified graduation exercises will be held June 20-27 for the STPPS Class of 2020 on campus at each of our eight high schools.

Ceremonies will be held indoors and will include the opportunity for graduates to wear their caps and gowns and receive their diplomas. Due to social distancing guidelines, all graduates, their families, and guests will not be allowed to congregate at the same time. Administrators at each high school are planning the ceremonies to best meet the needs of their individual school and community. Principals will be sharing additional information and logistics with their school communities. Please visit the school websites for schedules and details for each graduation.

The district and schools are taking steps to ensure that these celebrations are memorable and safe. The events will follow guidelines and protocols from local, state, and federal health officials to ensure the safety of graduates and others in attendance.

For details and information: www.stpsb.org/Class-of-2020/

#STPPSGrads

post_text: St. Tammany Parish President Mike Cooper talks with Dr. Tim Riddell, Regional Medical Director, Ochsner, and John Herman,Chief Executive Officer of the North Shore Region for Ochsner Health, during a walk-through today of the COVID-19 testing location in Mandeville, facilitated by Ochsner Health. The center at at Church of the King – Little Creek Campus, 22205 Little Creek Rd., Mandeville, will re-open tomorrow at 9 a.m. - 4 p.m. or until all testing kits have been utilized. There is no out-of-pocket expense, you can be tested whether you have symptoms or not. Testing is open to Louisiana residents, age two and older, who wish to know their status.Members of the community who wish to be tested should bring an ID and insurance card, if applicable. There are no out-of-pocket costs for those seeking a test and no one will be turned away based on their insurance status. Testing is available at the times listed or until all test kits have been utilized. Red etails here: http://www.stpgov.org/covid19 .

Road or Lane Status
LA 433, St. Tammany Parish, Lane Closure, S.P. H.012650
Friday, May 15, 2020 11:10 AM
There will be lane closures using flagging operations on LA 433, both directions, under the I-10 overpass beginning Monday, May 18, 2020, at 7AM through Friday, May 29, 2020, at 7PM, weather permitting, while crews perform bridge repair at the overpass.

One lane will remain open at all times.

Detour Information:
The following is an alternative route to avoid the work zone:

Motorist traveling LA 433 north may take US 90 north to US 190, then north to US 11, then south to re-intersect LA 433.
Motorists traveling LA 433 south may take US 11 north to US 190, then south to US 90, then south to re-intersect LA 433.

Permit Information:
There will be no vehicle restrictions, and emergency vehicles will have access. Motorists may encounter a slight delay during this time.

Friday, May 15, 2020 10:15 AM
UPDATE: EMERGENCY ROAD CLOSURE: LA 1085 between LA 1077 and I-12 is now closed to through traffic.

DETOUR: Motorists traveling north on LA 1085 should detour to LA 22 East, then LA 1077 North to I-12. Travel East on I-12 to LA 21, North on LA 21 to Bootlegger Road to return to LA 1085.

Motorists traveling south on LA 1085 should detour to LA 1077 South to LA 22. Travel LA 22 West to return to LA 1085.

DOTD appreciates your patience and reminds you to drive safely and be on the lookout for workers, equipment, or water on the roadway.
